        Hint: Edit the proof in <xref ref="act_proof_quants_nested"></xref><xref ref="part_proof_exists_forall"/>.
      </p>
    </subsubsection>
    <subsubsection>
      <title><xref ref="exer_rational_soln"></xref>  Select Answers and Hints</title>
      <p>
        Hint: Edit the proof in <xref ref="act_proof_quants_nested"></xref>
        <xref ref="part_proof_forall_exists"/>.
      </p>
    </subsubsection>
    <subsubsection>
      <title><xref ref="exer_cex_graphs"></xref> Select Answers and Hints</title>
      <ol>
        <li>
          <p>
            Hint: Your graph should have five vertices but not five edges.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            Hint: Your graph should have more edges than vertices.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            Hint: Your graph should have five vertices and not be <m>C_5</m> or <m>K_5</m>.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            Hint: Your graph should have at least two different numbers in its degree sequence.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            Hint: Look <xref ref="exam_chromatic_K4_C5">at</xref>
            <xref ref="part_chromatic_K4"/>.
            That is not a counterexample,
            but you can generalize to find a counterexample.
          </p>
        </li>
      </ol>
    </subsubsection>
    <subsubsection>
      <title><xref ref="exer_cex_numberthy"></xref> Select Answers and Hints</title>
      <ol>
        <li>
          <p>
            Hint: There is only one even prime.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            Hint: One counterexample is <m>15=3 \times 5</m>.
            Find a different counterexample.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            Hint: Find two composites that are not coprime.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            Hint: The number 1 is not prime.
          </p>
        </li>
      </ol>
    </subsubsection>
    <subsubsection>
      <title><xref ref="exer_neg_numberthy"></xref> Select Answers and Hints</title>
      <ol>
        <li>
          <p>
            Some integers are divisible by three or five.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            Hint: <xref ref="thm_demorgans">Use</xref>.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            Hint:
            <q>No</q>
            indicates the universal quantifier.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            Hint: Try starting the negation with
            <q>No</q>.
          </p>
        </li>
      </ol>
    </subsubsection>
  </subsection>
